  "prompt": "How do I solve [math]\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)[/math]?",
  "response": "To solve the limit \n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x\\right),\n\\]\n\nwe start by simplifying the expression inside the limit. First, notice that we can factor out \\(x^3\\) from the term under the cube root:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3 + x^2} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3(1 - \\frac{x^2}{x^3})} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3\\left(1 - \\frac{1}{x}\\right)}.\n\\]\n\nThis can be rewritten as:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{-x^3} \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} = -x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}.\n\\]\n\nNow, substituting this back into our original limit gives:\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left(-x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} + x\\right).\n\\]\n\nWe can simplify this expression further:\n\n\\[\n-x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} + x = x \\left(1 - \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}\\right).\n\\]\n\nNext, we need to analyze the term \\(\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}\\) as \\(x\\) approaches infinity. As \\(x \\to \\infty\\), \\(\\frac{1}{x} \\to 0\\), and thus:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} \\to \\sqrt[3]{1} = 1.\n\\]\n\nNow let's refine our expression:\n\n\\[\n1 - \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}.\n\\]\n\nUsing a first-order Taylor expansion around \\(\\frac{1}{x} = 0\\):\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{1 - y} \\approx 1 - \\frac{1}{3}y \\quad \\text{for small } y.\n\\]\n\nSetting \\(y = \\frac{1}{x}\\), we get:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} \\approx 1 - \\frac{1}{3}\\cdot\\frac{1}{x}.\n\\]\n\nTherefore:\n\n\\[\n1 - \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} \\approx \\frac{1}{3}\\cdot\\frac{1}{x}.\n\\]\n\nSubstituting this back into our limit gives:\n\n\\[\nx \\left(1 - \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}\\right) \\approx x \\cdot \\frac{1}{3}\\cdot\\frac{1}{x} = \\frac{1}{3}.\n\\]\n\nFinally, we conclude that:\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x\\right) = \\frac{1}{3}.\n\\]\n\nThus, the answer is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\frac{1}{3}}.\n\\]",
